We can also create a new column from an older.
In fact in the column "Name" there is 3 information (Lastname, Title. Firstname) separated by ',' and '.'.
Using the same separator '|', we can easily create a new column "Title" from the column name spliting information according to the separator.

In [2]:
titanic_df['Name'] = titanic_df['Name'].str.replace(',', '|')
titanic_df['Name'] = titanic_df['Name'].str.replace('.', '|')
titanic_df = titanic_df.join(titanic_df['Name'].apply(lambda x: pd.Series(x.split('|'))))

titanic_df['Firstname'] = titanic_df[0]
titanic_df['Title'] = titanic_df[1]
titanic_df['Lastname'] = titanic_df[2]
del titanic_df['Name']
del titanic_df[0]
del titanic_df[1]
del titanic_df[2]
del titanic_df[3]

I. B - Intuitive Prediction


Now that we have been able to clean / observe our dataframe we will be able to begin the study of this one by first looking at how many survivors there were for how many deaths and then proportions of these numbers.

Now we will replace values of the Survived column
Yes -> 1
No -> 0

In [8]:
titanic_df.Survived = titanic_df.Survived.map(dict(Yes=1, No=0))

So we can see that only 38% of passengers have survived.
We will create a new column 'Survived_Hypo' considering initially that all the passengers are dead.
It is this column that will be modified gradually to create our model of prediction.
Logically, our model will then be just at 62%.

In [9]:
titanic_df['Survived_Hypo'] = 0

We can create a function that will determine (using a temp column) how close our model is to the reality.

In [10]:
def comparaison_modele_realite(df):
  df['Comp'] = np.where(df['Survived'] == df['Survived_Hypo'], 1, 0)
  print (round(df['Comp'].sum()*100/len(df)),"% close to the reality")
  del df['Comp']

comparaison_modele_realite(titanic_df)

62.0 % close to the reality

We find well 62%.
Now we can work on a new mortality factor such as sex

So we have to change our 'Survived_Hypo' column and make sure all women survived.

Another way to calculate the link between two columns is to use the method accuracy_score from 'sklearn.metrics' library.

In [13]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

accuracy_score(titanic_df.Survived, titanic_df.Survived_Hypo)
Out[13]:
0.78675645342312006

After that, our model is even closer to reality 62 -> 79
Unfortunately not all women survived. We will therefore look for a criterion that could divide the women, such as age or wealth (the cost of the ticket / class in the boat).
Let's say that 25% of the women who bought the cheapest tickets died.

In [14]:
titanic_df.Survived_Hypo = 0
titanic_df.loc[(titanic_df.Sex == "female"), "Survived_Hypo"] = 1

quart_age = int((titanic_df.Fare.quantile([.25])))
titanic_df.loc[(titanic_df.Sex == "female") 
               & (titanic_df.Fare <= quart_age) 
               & (titanic_df.Pclass == 3), "Survived_Hypo"] = 0

accuracy_score(titanic_df.Survived, titanic_df.Survived_Hypo)
Out[14]:
0.78787878787878785


PART II: MACHINE LEARNING ALGORITHMS

II. A. a - Random Forest: Importance of variables


We will realize a new prediction by recovering the most important variables in the decision of survival of the passengers.
Firstly the idea is to import all the libraries needed for our work.
Then we must know that we can only work with numerical values, so we will replace men by 1 and women by 0 and thene Title by numbers from 0 to 16.

In [15]:
from pandas import Series, DataFrame
import matplotlib.pylab as plt
import sklearn.metrics
from sklearn import preprocessing

# Initialize label encoder
label_encoder = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
# Convert some variables to numeric
titanic_df["Sex"] = label_encoder.fit_transform(titanic_df["Sex"])
titanic_df["Title"] = label_encoder.fit_transform(titanic_df["Title"])
titanic_df.head(3)
Out[15]:
Title Firstname Lastname Sex Age Pclass Fare Embarked Survived Survived_Hypo
0 8 O'Sullivan Bridget Mary 0 28.0 3 7.6292 Q 0 1
1 8 Laitinen Kristina Sofia 0 37.0 3 9.5875 S 0 1
2 11 Daly Eugene Patrick 1 29.0 3 7.7500 Q 1 0

We will select the set of variables that interest us:

1. Sex
2. Age
3. Ticket price
4. Class in the boat
From then we define only one target that will naturally be our Survived column.
Then the idea is to make a prediction with 'predictors' on a random part of our data (.4 here -> 40% of 891 equal to 357) it's bootstrap principle.

In [16]:
from sklearn.cross_validation import train_test_split

features = ['Age', 'Sex', 'Fare', 'Pclass'] 
predictors = titanic_df[features]
target = titanic_df.Survived
split = train_test_split(titanic_df, target, test_size=0.4, random_state=42)
data_train, data_test, target_train, target_test = split
print('full shape:', titanic_df.shape, '\ntest shape:', data_test.shape, '\ntrain shape:', data_train.shape)

full shape: (891, 10) 
test shape: (357, 10) 
train shape: (534, 10)

The objective is now to rank the selected variables in order of importance.
We will now realize a RandomForest on our 40% extracted data.
First, we need to import useful libraries.
Then we'll display the importance of each columns and the error estimation using barplot.

In [17]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier as RandomForest

model = RandomForest(n_estimators=10)
model.fit(data_train[features], target_train)
importances = model.feature_importances_
std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in model.estimators_], axis=0)

for feature, imp, i in zip(features, importances, range(len(features))):
    print("  %d. %s -> %f" % (i+1, feature, imp))

# Plot the feature importances of the forest
plt.figure()
plt.title("Feature importances")
plt.bar(range(len(features)), importances, color="r", yerr=std, align="center")
plt.xticks(range(len(features)), np.array(features))
plt.xlim([-1, len(features)])
plt.show()

  
  1. Age -> 0.266334
  2. Sex -> 0.258859
  3. Fare -> 0.357780
  4. Pclass -> 0.117027


II. A. b - Random Forest: Score Prediction


The 'confusion matrix' is a square matrix whose diagonal (top left to bottom right) represents the number of values correctly predicted.
In the same way, metrics.accuracy_score will calculate a prediction score.
The set will never be equal from one compilation to the other due to the phenomenon of bootstrap which will in each case look for different data.

In [18]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

prediction = model.predict(data_test[features])
print("Confusion matrix:\n", sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(target_test, prediction))
print("\nScore:\n", sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score(target_test, prediction))

Confusion matrix:
 [[185  37]
 [ 30 105]]

Score:
 0.812324929972

Now it could be interesting to know if the creation of our 'Title' column was useful by using this one as a new feature.
So we could do exactly the same operation adding the Title column.

In [19]:
features = ['Sex', 'Pclass', 'Age', 'Fare', 'Title']
model = RandomForest(n_estimators=10)
model.fit(data_train[features], target_train)
importances = model.feature_importances_
std = np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in model.estimators_], axis=0)

for feature, imp, i in zip(features, importances, range(len(features))):
    print("  %d. %s -> %f" % (i+1, feature, imp))

# Plot the feature importances of the forest
plt.figure()
plt.title("Feature importances")
plt.bar(range(len(features)), importances, color="r", yerr=std, align="center")
plt.xticks(range(len(features)), np.array(features))

#Score
print('Performence:', model.score(data_test[features], target_test), '\n')

So we can see that our prediction improved meaning that our idea of create a Title column was good.

Then we will create a dataframe that will display the prediction proposed by the random forest and the reality (survivor = 1, dead = 0) and then compare them in a last column called 'get_it'.

In [20]:
print('==> predict: ')
prediction = model.predict(data_test[features])
reality = target_test
result = pd.DataFrame({'prediction': prediction,
                       'reality': reality})
result['get_it'] = 'non'
result.loc[result.prediction == result.reality, 'get_it'] = 'yes'

print(result.head(10))
print('  == get_it:')
print(result.get_it.value_counts())

II. B - Decision Tree

Now that we have seen the most important variables in the decision of passenger death, we can now make a decision tree including first sex which is a binary attribute making the decision tree more understandable.

In [21]:
# A nécessité d'un 'brew install graphviz' sur terminal
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn import tree
from io import StringIO
from IPython.display import Image
import pydotplus

#make classifier with our feature
features = ['Sex'] 
predictors = titanic_df[features]
targets = titanic_df.Survived
pred_train, pred_test, tar_train, tar_test = train_test_split(predictors, targets, test_size=.4)
classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(min_samples_split=20, random_state=10)
classifier = classifier.fit(pred_train, tar_train)

#Draw
out = StringIO()
tree.export_graphviz(classifier, out_file=out)
graph=pydotplus.graph_from_dot_data(out.getvalue())
Image(graph.create_png())
Out[21]:
